label: Study Identifier
IGcomment: Unique identifier for a study.

label: Domain Abbreviation
IGcomment: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

label: Unique Subject Identifier
comment: Concatenation of STUDYID and DM.SUBJID
IGcomment: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

label: Sponsor Device Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier for a device

label: Sequence Number
algorithm: Sequential number identifying records within each USUBJID
IGcomment: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

label: Group ID
IGcomment: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

label: Reference ID
IGcomment: Internal or external identifier such as a serial number on an SAE reporting form.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier. It may be pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on an Adverse Events page.

label: Link ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to- one or a one-to-many relationship. For Example: A single tumor may have multiple measurements/assessments performed at each study visit.

label: Link Group ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship. For example: Multiple tumor measurements/assessments will contribute to a single response to therapy determination record.

label: Reported Term for the Adverse Event
IGcomment: Verbatim name of the event.

label: Modified Reported Term
IGcomment: If AETERM is modified to facilitate coding, then AEMODIFY will contain the modified text.

label: Lowest Level Term
IGcomment: Dictionary-derived text description of the Lowest Level Term.

label: Lowest Level Term Code
IGcomment: Dictionary-derived code for the Lowest Level Term.

label: Dictionary-Derived Term
IGcomment: Dictionary-derived text description of AETERM or AEMODIFY. Equivalent to the Preferred Term (PT in MedDRA). The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes.

label: Preferred Term Code
IGcomment: Dictionary-derived code for the Preferred Term.

label: High Level Term
IGcomment: Dictionary-derived text description of the High Level Term for the primary System Organ Class.

label: High Level Term Code
IGcomment: Dictionary-derived code for the High Level Term for the primary System Organ Class.

label: High Level Group Term
IGcomment: Dictionary-derived text description of the High Level Group Term for the primary System Organ Class.

label: High Level Group Term Code
IGcomment: Dictionary-derived code for the High Level Group Term for the primary System Organ Class.

label: Category for Adverse Event
IGcomment: Used to define a category of related records. Example: BLEEDING, NEUROPSYCHIATRIC.

label: Subcategory for Adverse Event
IGcomment: A further categorization of adverse event. Example: NEUROLOGIC.

label: Pre-Specified Adverse Event
IGcomment: A value of "Y" indicates that this adverse event was pre-specified on the CRF. Values are null for spontaneously reported events (i.e., those collected as free- text verbatim terms)

label: Body System or Organ Class
IGcomment: Dictionary derived. Body system or organ class used by the sponsor from the coding dictionary (e.g., MedDRA). When using a multi-axial dictionary such as MedDRA, this should contain the SOC used for the sponsor's analyses and summary tables which may not necessarily be the primary SOC.

label: Body System or Organ Class Code
IGcomment: Dictionary derived. Code for the body system or organ class used by the sponsor. When using a multi-axial dictionary such as MedDRA, this should contain the SOC used for the sponsor's analyses and summary tables, which may not necessarily be the primary SOC.

label: Primary System Organ Class
IGcomment: Dictionary-derived text description of the primary System Organ Class. Will be the same as AEBODSYS if the primary SOC was used for analysis.

label: Primary System Organ Class Code
IGcomment: Dictionary-derived code for the primary System Organ Class. Will be the same as AEBDSYCD if the primary SOC was used for analysis.

label: Location of Event
IGcomment: Describes anatomical location relevant for the event (e.g., ARM for skin rash).

label: Severity/Intensity
IGcomment: The severity or intensity of the event. Examples: MILD, MODERATE, SEVERE.

label: Serious Event
IGcomment: Is this a serious event?

label: Action Taken with Study Treatment
IGcomment: Describes changes to the study treatment as a result of the event. AEACN is specifically for the relationship to study treatment. AEACNOTH is for actions unrelated to dose adjustments of study treatment. Examples of AEACN values include ICH E2B values: DRUG WITHDRAWN, DOSE REDUCED, DOSE INCREASED, DOSE NOT CHANGED, UNKNOWN or NOT APPLICABLE.

label: Other Action Taken
IGcomment: Describes other actions taken as a result of the event that are unrelated to dose adjustments of study treatment. Usually reported as free text. Example: "TREATMENT UNBLINDED. PRIMARY CARE PHYSICIAN NOTIFIED."

label: Action Taken with Device
IGcomment: Action taken with respect to a device in a study, which may or may not be the device under study

label: Causality
IGcomment: Records the investigator's opinion as to the causality of the event to the treatment. ICH E2A and E2B examples include NOT RELATED, UNLIKELY RELATED, POSSIBLY RELATED, RELATED. Controlled Terminology may be defined in the future. Check with regulatory authority for population of this variable.

label: Relationship to Non-Study Treatment
IGcomment: Records the investigator's opinion as to whether the event may have been due to a treatment other than study drug. May be reported as free text. Example: "MORE LIKELY RELATED TO ASPIRIN USE.".

label: Pattern of Adverse Event
IGcomment: Used to indicate the pattern of the event over time. Examples: INTERMITTENT, CONTINUOUS, SINGLE EVENT.

label: Outcome of Adverse Event
IGcomment: Description of the outcome of an event.

label: Involves Cancer
IGcomment: Was the serious event associated with the development of cancer?

label: Congenital Anomaly or Birth Defect
IGcomment: Was the serious event associated with congenital anomaly or birth defect?

label: Persist or Signif Disability/Incapacity
IGcomment: Did the serious event result in persistent or significant disability/incapacity?

label: Results in Death
algorithm: If AE record exists with AEOUT=FATAL then AESDTH=Y
IGcomment: Did the serious event result in death?

label: Requires or Prolongs Hospitalization
IGcomment: Did the serious event require or prolong hospitalization?

label: Is Life Threatening
IGcomment: Was the serious event life threatening?

label: Occurred with Overdose
IGcomment: Did the serious event occur with an overdose?

label: Other Medically Important Serious Event
IGcomment: Do additional categories for seriousness apply?

label: Concomitant or Additional Trtmnt Given
IGcomment: Was another treatment given because of the occurrence of the event?

label: Standard Toxicity Grade
IGcomment: Toxicity grade according to a standard toxicity scale such as Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events v3.0 (CTCAE). Sponsor should specify name of the scale and version used in the metadata (see Assumption 6d). If value is from a numeric scale, represent only the number (e.g., "2" and not "Grade 2").

label: Epi/Pandemic Related Indicator
IGcomment: Non-standard Variable from Guidance for Ongoing Studies Disrupted by COVID-19 Pandemic Version 1.0

label: Element Code
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

label: Description of Element
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: The name of the Element.

label: Epoch
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected. (See Section 3.2.2).

label: Study Day of Start of Adverse Event
algorithm: Calculation: = AESTDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if AESTDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,AESTDTC - RFSTDTC if AESTDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Study day of start of adverse event relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

label: Study Day of End of Adverse Event
algorithm: Calculation: = AEENDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if AEENDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,AEENDTC - RFSTDTC if AEENDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Study day of end of event relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

label: Duration of Adverse Event
IGcomment: Collected duration and unit of an adverse event. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times. Example: P1DT2H (for 1 day, 2 hours).

label: End Relative to Reference Period
IGcomment: Describes the end of the event relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point (RFSTDTC) and a discrete ending point (RFENDTC) of the trial. This variable is proposed for deletion post SDTM V1.4.

label: Start Relative to Reference Time Point
End Relative to Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Identifies the end of the event as being before or after the reference time point defined by variable AEENTPT.

label: End Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Description of date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by AEENRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-25" or "VISIT 2".

label: Unique Subject Identifier
comment: Concatenation of STUDYID and DM.SUBJID

label: Sponsor Device Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier for a device

label: Sequence Number
algorithm: Sequential number identifying records within each USUBJID

label: Reference ID
IGcomment: Optional internal or external identifier such as lab specimen ID, or UUID for an ECG waveform or a medical image.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
comment: System generated unique identifier, can be used as reference to the ADaM domains

IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to- one or a one-to-many relationship. For Example: A single tumor may have multiple measurements/assessments performed at each study visit.

label: Link Group ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship. For example: Multiple tumor measurements/assessments will contribute to a single response to therapy determination record.

comment: Set to NOT DONE if 'ND', 'NA', 'NK' ,' ' have been reported on CRF

comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: The name of the Element.

comment: Multiple unscheduled visits or non-visits can exist having the same visit ID but with different dates. This might result in duplicate records for the same visit number but with different dates

comment: Based on TV.VISITDY

algorithm: Calculation: = AGSTDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if AGSTDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,AGSTDTC - RFSTDTC if AGSTDTC precedes RFSTDTC

label: Planned Time Point Name
IGcomment: Text description of time when a measurement or observation should be taken as defined in the protocol. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See --TPTNUM and -- TPTREF.

label: Planned Time Point Number
IGcomment: Numeric version of planned time point used in sorting.

label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
IGcomment: Planned Elapsed time in ISO 8601 character format relative to a planned fixed reference (--TPTREF) such as "Previous Dose" or "Previous Meal". This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration.

label: Time Point Reference
IGcomment: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by --ELTM, --TPTNUM, and --TPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by --TPTREF in ISO 8601 character format.

End Relative to Reference Time Point
Study Identifier

label: Domain Abbreviation
IGcomment: Four-character abbreviation for the domain, AP--.

label: Associated Persons Identifier
IGcomment: Identifier for a single associated person, a group of associated persons, or a pool of associated persons. If APID identifies a pool, POOLDEF records must exist for each associated person.

label: Sequence Number
IGcomment: Sequence number to ensure uniqueness of records within a domain for associated persons. Unique within APID within the domain.

label: Related Subject
IGcomment: Identifier for a related study subject or pool of study subjects. The subject(s) may be human or animal. RSUBJID will be populated with the USUBJID of the related subject or the POOLID of the related pool. RSUBJID will be null for data about associated persons who are related to the study but not to any of the study subjects.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
comment: System generated unique identifier, required for Enriched SDTM generation.

label: Related Device
IGcomment: Identifier for a related device. RDEVID will be populated with the SPDEVID of the related device.

label: Subject, Device, or Study Relationship
IGcomment: If RSUBJID is populated, describes the relationship of the associated person(s) identified in APID to the subject or pool identified in RSUBJID. If RDEVID is populated, describes the relationship of the associated person(s) identified in APID to the device identified in RDEVID. If RSUBJID and RDEVID are null, SREL describes the relationship of the associated person(s) identified in APID to the study identified in STUDYID.

algorithm: Classifies the start of the medication relative to reference period as defined by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics.

The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). label: End Relative to Reference Period
algorithm: Classifies the end of the medication relative to reference period as defined by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics. If reported as ongoing on the CRF, the value will be set to ONGOING.

label: Reported Name of Drug, Med, or Therapy
IGcomment: Verbatim medication name that is either pre-printed or collected on a CRF.

label: Modified Reported Name
IGcomment: If CMTRT is modified to facilitate coding, then CMMODIFY will contain the modified text.

label: Standardized Medication Name
IGcomment: Standardized or dictionary-derived text description of CMTRT or CMMODIFY. Equivalent to the generic medication name in WHO Drug. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes. If an intervention term does not have a decode value in the dictionary then CMDECOD will be left blank.

label: Category for Medication
IGcomment: Used to define a category of medications/treatments. Examples: PRIOR, CONCOMITANT, ANTI-CANCER MEDICATION, or GENERAL CONMED.

label: Subcategory for Medication
IGcomment: A further categorization of medications/ treatment. Examples: CHEMOTHERAPY, HORMONAL THERAPY, ALTERNATIVE THERAPY.

label: CM Pre-Specified
IGcomment: Used to indicate whether (Y/null) information about the use of a specific medication was solicited on the CRF.

label: CM Occurrence
IGcomment: When the use of specific medications is solicited, CMOCCUR is used to indicate whether or not (Y/N) use of the medication occurred. Values are null for medications not specifically solicited.

label: Completion Status
algorithm: Set to NOT DONE if 'ND', 'NA', 'NK' ,' ' have been reported on CRF
IGcomment: Used to indicate that a question about a pre-specified medication was not answered. Should be null or have a value of NOT DONE.

label: Reason Medication Not Collected
IGcomment: Describes the reason concomitant medication was not collected. Used in conjunction with CMSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

label: Indication
IGcomment: Denotes why a medication was taken or administered. Examples: NAUSEA, HYPERTENSION.

label: Medication Class
IGcomment: Drug class. May be obtained from coding. When coding to a single class, populate with class value. If using a dictionary and coding to multiple classes, then follow Section 4: 4.1.2.8.3, Multiple Values For A Non-Result Qualifier Variable or omit CMCLAS.

label: Medication Class Code
IGcomment: Class code corresponding to CMCLAS. Drug class. May be obtained from coding. When coding to a single class, populate with class code. If using a dictionary and coding to multiple classes, then follow Section 4: 4.1.2.8.3, Multiple Values For A Non-Result Qualifier Variable or omit CMCLASCD.

label: Dose per Administration
IGcomment: Amount of CMTRT taken. Not populated when CMDOSTXT is populated.

label: Dose Description
IGcomment: Dosing amounts or a range of dosing information collected in text form. Units may be stored in CMDOSU. Example: 200-400, 15-20. Not populated when CMDOSE is populated.

label: Dose Units
IGcomment: Units for CMDOSE, CMDOSTOT, and CMDOSTXT. Examples: ng, mg, or mg/kg.

label: Dose Form
IGcomment: Dose form for CMTRT. Examples: TABLET, LOTION.

label: Dosing Frequency per Interval
IGcomment: Usually expressed as the number of repeated administrations of CMDOSE within a specific time period. Examples: BID (twice daily), Q12H (every 12 hours).

label: Total Daily Dose
IGcomment: Total daily dose of CMTRT using the units in CMDOSU. Used when dosing is collected as Total Daily Dose. Total dose over a period other than day could be recorded in a separate Supplemental Qualifier variable.

label: Intended Dose Regimen
IGcomment: Text description of the (intended) schedule or regimen for the Intervention. Examples: TWO WEEKS ON, TWO WEEKS OFF.

label: Route of Administration
IGcomment: Route of administration for CMTRT. Examples: ORAL, INTRAVENOUS.

label: Element Code
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

label: Description of Element
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: The name of the Element.

label: Epoch
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected. (See Section 3.2.2).

IGcomment: Study day of start of medication relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

algorithm: Calculation: = CMENDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if CMENDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,CMENDTC - RFSTDTC if CMENDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Study day of end of medication relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

label: Duration of Medication
IGcomment: Collected duration for a treatment episode. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times.

label: Planned Time Point Name

label: Planned Time Point Number

IGcomment: Planned Elapsed time in ISO 8601 character format relative to a planned fixed reference (--TPTREF) such as "Previous Dose" or "Previous Meal". label: Time Point Reference
IGcomment: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by --ELTM, --TPTNUM, and --TPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point

IGcomment: Describes the start of the medication relative to sponsor-defined reference period. If information such as "PRIOR", ONGOING or "CONTINUING" was collected, this information may be translated into CMSTRF. This variable is proposed for deletion post SDTM V1.4.

label: Question Short Name
IGcomment: Topic variable for QS. Short name for the value in QSTEST, which can be used as a column name when converting the dataset from a vertical format to a horizontal format. The value in QSTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g."1TEST"). QSTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. See QS Terminology Spreadsheet for specific text for QSTESTCD. Examples: ADCCMD01, BPR0103

label: Question Name
IGcomment: Verbatim name of the question or group of questions used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in QSTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. See QS Terminology Spreadsheet for specific text for QSTEST. Example: Fist, BPR01 - Emotional Withdrawal

label: Category of Question
IGcomment: Used to define a category of related records that will be meaningful to the Reviewer. See QS Terminology Spreadsheet for specific text for QSCAT. Examples: ADAS-COG, MDS-UPDRS.

label: Subcategory for Question
IGcomment: A further categorization of the questions within the category. Examples: MENTAL HEALTH DOMAIN, DEPRESSION DOMAIN, WORD RECALL.

label: Finding in Original Units
IGcomment: Finding as originally received or collected (e.g. RARELY, SOMETIMES). When sponsors apply codelist to indicate the code values are statistically meaningful standardized scores, which are defined by sponsors or by valid methodologies such as SF36 questionnaires, QSORRES will contain the decode format, and QSSTRESC and QSSTRESN may contain the standardized code values or scores.

label: Original Units
IGcomment: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for QSORRES, such as minutes or seconds or the units associated with a visual analog scale.

label: Result or Finding in Standard Format
algorithm: QSORRES converted into standard unit
IGcomment: Contains the finding for all questions or sub-scores, copied or derived from QSORRES in a standard format or standard units. QSSTRESC should store all findings in character format; if findings are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in QSSTRESN. If question scores are derived from the original finding, then the standard format is the score. Examples: 0, 1. When sponsors apply codelist to indicate the code values are statistically meaningful standardized scores, which are defined by sponsors or by valid methodologies such as SF36 questionnaires, QSORRES will contain the decode format, and QSSTRESC and QSSTRESN may contain the standardized code values or scores.

label: Numeric Finding in Standard Units
algorithm: QSORRES converted into standard unit
IGcomment: Used for continuous or numeric findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from QSSTRESC. QSSTRESN should store all numeric results or findings.

label: Standard Units
IGcomment: Standardized unit used for QSSTRESC or QSSTRESN.

label: Completion Status
algorithm: Set to NOT DONE if 'ND', 'NA', 'NK' ,' ' have been reported on CRF
IGcomment: Used to indicate a questionnaire or response to a questionnaire was not done. Should be null if a result exists in QSORRES.

label: Reason Not Performed
algorithm: Set to NOT COLLECTED if QSSTAT is set to NOT DONE
IGcomment: Describes why a question was not answered. Used in conjunction with QSSTAT when value is NOT DONE. Example: SUBJECT REFUSED.

label: Baseline Flag
algorithm: Baseline flag set to Y when the assessment is collected at the visit marked as baseline in the trial flowchart
IGcomment: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be "Y" or null.

label: Derived Flag
IGcomment: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records that represent the average of other records or questionnaire sub-scores that do not come from the CRF are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If QSDRVFL=Y, then QSORRES may be null with QSSTRESC and (if numeric) QSSTRESN having the derived value.

label: Assessment Result in Std Format
IGcomment: Contains the result value for all Drug Accountability assessments, copied or derived from DAORRES in a standard format or in standard units. DASTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in DASTRESN.

label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
IGcomment: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from DASTRESC. DASTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

label: Assessment Standard Units
IGcomment: Standardized units used for DASTRESC and DASTRESN.

label: Completion Status
algorithm: Set to NOT DONE if 'ND', 'NA', 'NK' ,' ' have been reported on CRF
IGcomment: Used to indicate that a drug accountability assessment was not done. Should be null or have a value of NOT DONE.

label: Reason Not Performed
IGcomment: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with DASTAT when value is NOT DONE.

label: Evaluator
IGcomment: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Examples: ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR, RADIOLOGIST.

label: Evaluator Identifier
IGcomment: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in --EVAL. Examples: RADIOLOGIST1 or RADIOLOGIST2

label: Element Code
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

label: Description of Element
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: The name of the Element.

label: Visit Number
IGcomment: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

label: Visit Name
IGcomment: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY

label: Planned Study Day of Visit
comment: Based on TV.VISITDY
IGcomment: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

label: Epoch
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected. (See Section 3.2.2).

label: Study Day of Accountability Assessment
algorithm: Calculation: = DADTC - RFSTDTC+1 if DADTC is on or after RFSTDTC,DADTC - RFSTDTC if DADTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: 1. Study day of drug accountability assessment, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

label: Planned Time Point Name
IGcomment: Text description of time when a measurement or observation should be taken as defined in the protocol. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See --TPTNUM and -- TPTREF.

label: Planned Time Point Number
IGcomment: Numeric version of planned time point used in sorting.

label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
IGcomment: Planned Elapsed time in ISO 8601 character format relative to a planned fixed reference (--TPTREF) such as "Previous Dose" or "Previous Meal". This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration.

label: Time Point Reference
IGcomment: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by --ELTM, --TPTNUM, and --TPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by --TPTREF in ISO 8601 character format.

label: Study Identifier
IGcomment: Unique identifier for a study.

label: Domain Abbreviation
IGcomment: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

label: Unique Subject Identifier
comment: Concatenation of STUDYID and DM.SUBJID
IGcomment: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

label: Sequence Number
IGcomment: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier. Example: pre-printed line identifier on a Concomitant Medications page.

label: Link ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to- one or a one-to-many relationship. For Example: A single tumor may have multiple measurements/assessments performed at each study visit.

label: Link Group ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship. For example: Multiple tumor measurements/assessments will contribute to a single response to therapy determination record.

label: Death Detail Assessment Short Name
IGcomment: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in DDTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in DDTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). DDTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: DIAGPRIM, DIAGSEC, DTHWIT

label: Death Detail Assessment Name
IGcomment: Long name for DDTESTCD. The value in DDTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Primary Diagnosis, Secondary Diagnosis, Was Death Witnessed?

label: Result or Finding as Collected
IGcomment: Result of the test defined in DDTEST, as originally received or collected.

label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
IGcomment: Contains the result or finding copied or derived from DDORRES in a standard format.

label: Result Category
IGcomment: Used to categorize the result of a finding. Examples: TREATMENT RELATED, NONTREATMENT RELATED, UNDETERMINED, ACCIDENTAL

label: Evaluator
IGcomment: Role of the person who provided the evaluation.

label: Evaluator Identifier
IGcomment: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in --EVAL. Examples: RADIOLOGIST1 or RADIOLOGIST2

label: Element Code
IGcomment: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

label: Description of Element
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: The name of the Element.

label: Epoch
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected. (See Section 3.2.2).

label: Date/Time of Collection
IGcomment: Date/time of collection of the diagnosis or other death assessment data in ISO 8601 format. This is not necessarily the date of death.

label: Study Day of Collection
algorithm: Calculation: = DDDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if DDDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,DDDTC - RFSTDTC if DDDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Study day of the collection, in integer days. The algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in the Demographics (DM) domain.

label: Study Identifier
IGcomment: Unique identifier for a study.

label: Domain Abbreviation
IGcomment: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

label: Unique Subject Identifier
comment: Concatenation of STUDYID and DM.SUBJID
IGcomment: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product. Expected rather than required because events may happen to or with a device that do not involved subjects, and may even be before the device was in contact with a subject. In these cases there may not be a value for USUBJID.

label: Sponsor Device Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier for the device. It must be unique for each tracked unit of the device under study, and can be at whatever level of granularity the device should be identified (e.g., model or serial number, or combination of identifiers).

label: Device Events Sequence Number
IGcomment: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of device records within subject records within a domain. May be any valid number. It should be unique within every subject/device combination. If there is no USUBJID associated with the event, DESEQ should be unique within each SPDEVID.

label: Reference ID
IGcomment: Optional internal or external identifier such as lab specimen ID, or UUID for an ECG waveform or a medical image.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Note that it does not have to be numeric.

label: Link ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to- one or a one-to-many relationship. For Example: A single tumor may have multiple measurements/assessments performed at each study visit.

label: Link Group ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship. For example: Multiple tumor measurements/assessments will contribute to a single response to therapy determination record.

label: Reported Term for Device Event
IGcomment: Verbatim name of the observed event. Examples: Screw Breakage, Fissure Formation, Battery Issue

label: Modified Device Event Name
IGcomment: The modified text for DETERM. If DETERM is modified, then the modified text is placed here.

label: Device Events Dictionary-Derived Term
IGcomment: Dictionary-derived form of the event described in DETERM. Dictionary-derived text description of DETERM or DEMODIFY. 'The name and version of the dictionary used to map terms must be provided in a Define.XML ExternalCodeList element.

label: Category of Device Event
IGcomment: Used to define a categorization level for events. For example, MALFUNCTION vs. CALIBRATION

label: Subcategory of Device Event
IGcomment: Used to define a further category level for events. For example, EXTERNAL vs. INTERNAL

label: Pre-Specified Device Event
IGcomment: Used to indicate whether (Y/null) information about a specific event was solicited on the CRF. For example, DETERM could contain a list of malfunctions that are being specifically evaluated. DEPRESP would identify those (Y), while any spontaneous events would have DEPREST = null.

label: Device Event Occurrence
IGcomment: When information about specific events is solicited, DEOCCUR is used to indicate whether or not (Y/N) a particular pre-specified event occurred. Values are null for events not specifically solicited.

label: Device Event Collection Status
IGcomment: The status indicates that the pre-specified question was not answered. For example, if equipment operation requires checking, such as checking an event log to detect events. Capturing that the checks were not completed may be relevant to interpreting the study data.

label: Reason Device Event Not Collected
IGcomment: Reason DESTAT was "not done". This variable should only be used if there are prespecified events.

label: Device Event Severity
IGcomment: Severity of Event. Terms Describing Severity of Event (e.g., the severity of a Malfunction)

label: Action Taken with Device
IGcomment: Describes Action Taken with respect to the device. Action Taken may include removal, calibration, reprogramming, etc. Action is usually in response to some event, for example, a subject's adverse event

label: Element Code
IGcomment: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

label: Description of Element
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: The name of the Element.

label: Visit Number
IGcomment: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

label: Visit Name
IGcomment: Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

label: Planned Study Day of Visit
comment: Based on TV.VISITDY
IGcomment: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics. This value is usually derived.

label: Epoch
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected. (See Section 3.2.2).

label: Date of Device Event Data Collection
IGcomment: Date the device event information was collected. This may be reported if the event (e.g., malfunction) is discovered on a different date from the event

label: Start Date/Time of Device Event
IGcomment: Start date/time of the device event. If the event happened at a single point in time, DESTDTC is used.

label: End Date/Time of Device Event
IGcomment: End date/time of the device event. If an event lasted over a period of time, DEENDTC can be used to capture the end date/time.

label: Study Day of DE Start Date/Time
algorithm: Calculation: = DEDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if DEDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,DEDTC - RFSTDTC if DEDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Study day of Device Event observation, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

label: Study Day of DE Start Date/Time
algorithm: Calculation: = DESTDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if DESTDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,DESTDTC - RFSTDTC if DESTDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Study day of start of Device Event, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

label: Study Day of Device Event End Date/Time
algorithm: Calculation: = DEENDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if DEENDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,DEENDTC - RFSTDTC if DEENDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Study day of end of Device Event, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFENDTC variable in Demographics.

label: Study Identifier
IGcomment: Unique identifier for a study.

label: Domain Abbreviation
IGcomment: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

label: Sponsor Device Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier for the device. It must be unique for each tracked unit of the device under study, and can be at whatever level of granularity the device should be identified (e.g., model or serial number, or combination of identifiers).

label: Unique Subject Identifier
comment: Concatenation of STUDYID and DM.SUBJID (This is a variable for internal system use)
IGcomment: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

label: Sequence Number
IGcomment: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness within a parameter within a device (SPDEVID) within dataset. If there is only one value for DIPARMCD for each value of SPDEVID, then DISEQ will be 1 for all records. DISEQ must be a valid number.

label: Device Identifier Element Short Name
IGcomment: Short name of the identifier characteristic of the device. Examples: SERIAL, MODEL. A record with DIPARMCD = TYPE should be included (see below)

label: Device Identifier Element Name
IGcomment: Name of the identifier characteristic of the device. Examples: Serial Number, Model. A record with DIPARM = Type should be included (see below)

label: Device Identifier Element Value
IGcomment: Value for the parameter. Value for the parameter. When DIPARM = Type, DIVAL should be a value in the GMDN dictionary (see below)

label: Study Identifier
IGcomment: Unique identifier for a study.

label: Domain Abbreviation
IGcomment: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

label: Unique Subject Identifier
comment: Concatenation of STUDYID and DM.SUBJID
IGcomment: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product. This must be a unique number, and could be a compound identifier formed by concatenating STUDYID-SITEID-SUBJID.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
comment: System generated unique identifier, can be used as reference to the ADaM domains
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier. Example: pre-printed line identifier on a Concomitant Medications page.

label: Subject Identifier for the Study
IGcomment: Subject identifier, which must be unique within the study. Often the ID of the subject as recorded on a CRF.

label: Subject Reference Start Date/Time
algorithm: Derived from DS.DSSTDTC where DSTERM=FIRST TRIAL PRODUCT DATE DURING RUN-IN, otherwise DSTERM=FIRST DATE ON TRIAL PRODUCT
IGcomment: Reference Start Date/time for the subject in ISO 8601 character format. Usually equivalent to date/time when subject was first exposed to study treatment. Required for all randomized subjects; will be null for all subjects who did not meet the milestone the date requires, such as screen failures or unassigned subjects.

label: Subject Reference End Date/Time
algorithm: Derived from DS.DSSTDTC where DSTERM=LAST DATE ON TRIAL PRODUCT
IGcomment: Reference End Date/time for the subject in ISO 8601 character format. Usually equivalent to the date/time when subject was determined to have ended the trial, and often equivalent to date/time of last exposure to study treatment. Required for all randomized subjects; null for screen failures or unassigned subjects.

label: Date/Time of First Study Treatment
algorithm: Derived from DS.DSSTDTC where DSTERM=FIRST DATE ON TRIAL PRODUCT
IGcomment: First date of exposure to any protocol-specified treatment or therapy, equal to the earliest value of EXSTDTC.

label: Date/Time of Last Study Treatment
algorithm: Derived from DS.DSSTDTC where DSTERM=LAST DATE ON TRIAL PRODUCT, otherwise LAST TRIAL PRODUCT DATE DURING RUN-IN
IGcomment: Last date of exposure to any protocol-specified treatment or therapy, equal to the latest value of EXENDTC (or the latest value of EXSTDTC if EXENDTC was not collected or is missing).

label: Date/Time of Informed Consent
algorithm: If multiple DS records exist with DSDECOD=INFORMED CONSENT OBTAINED and various DSTERM then RFICDTC is set to the last DSSTDTC, else first DSSTDTC
IGcomment: Date/time of informed consent in ISO 8601 character format. This will be the same as the date of informed consent in the Disposition domain, if that protocol milestone is documented. Would be null only in studies not collecting the date of informed consent.

label: Date/Time of End of Participation
algorithm: Derived as the maximum date present in any --DTC, --STDTC or --ENDTC variable in any SDTM dataset, except DV, for each USUBJID
IGcomment: Date/time when subject ended participation or follow-up in a trial, as defined in the protocol, in ISO 8601 character format. Should correspond to the last known date of contact. Examples include completion date, withdrawal date, last follow-up, date recorded for lost to follow up, or death date.

label: Date/Time of Death
algorithm: If DD record exists with non-missing DDDTC then DTHDTC=DDDTC or AE record exists with AESDTH=Y then DTHDTC=AEENDTC
IGcomment: Date/time of death for any subject who died, in ISO 8601 format. Should represent the date/time that is captured in the clinical-trial database.

label: Subject Death Flag
algorithm: If DTHDTC is not missing or DD record exists or AE record exists with AESDTH=Y then DTHFL=Y
IGcomment: Indicates the subject died. Should be Y or null. Should be populated even when the death date is unknown.

label: Study Site Identifier
IGcomment: Unique identifier for a site within a study.

label: Investigator Identifier
IGcomment: An identifier to describe the Investigator for the study. May be used in addition to SITEID. Not needed if SITEID is equivalent to INVID.

label: Investigator Name
IGcomment: Name of the investigator for a site.

label: Date/Time of Birth
IGcomment: Date/time of birth of the subject.

label: Age
comment: Age at start of trial
IGcomment: Age expressed in AGEU. May be derived from RFSTDTC and BRTHDTC, but BRTHDTC may not be available in all cases (due to subject privacy concerns).

label: Age Units
IGcomment: Units associated with AGE.

label: Sex
IGcomment: Sex of the subject.

label: Race
IGcomment: Race of the subject. Sponsors should refer to "Collection of Race and Ethnicity Data in Clinical Trials" (FDA, September 2005) for guidance regarding the collection of race (http://www.fda.gov/RegulatoryInformation/Guidances/ucm126340.htm) See Assumption below regarding RACE.

label: Ethnicity
IGcomment: The ethnicity of the subject. Sponsors should refer to "Collection of Race and Ethnicity Data in Clinical Trials" (FDA, September 2005) for guidance regarding the collection of ethnicity (http://www.fda.gov/RegulatoryInformation/Guidances/ucm126340.htm).

label: Planned Arm Code
IGcomment: ARMCD is limited to 20 characters and does not have special character restrictions. The maximum length of ARMCD is longer than for other "short" variables to accommodate the kind of values that are likely to be needed for crossover trials. For example, if ARMCD values for a seven-period crossover were constructed using two- character abbreviations for each treatment and separating hyphens, the length of ARMCD values would be 20.

label: Description of Planned Arm
IGcomment: Name of the Arm to which the subject was assigned.

label: Actual Arm Code
IGcomment: Code of actual Arm. When an Arm is not planned (not in Trial Arms), ACTARMCD will be UNPLAN. Randomized subjects who were not treated will be given a value of NOTTRT. Values should be "SCRNFAIL" for screen failures and "NOTASSGN" for subjects not assigned to treatment. Restricted to values in Trial Arms in all other cases. ACTARMCD is limited to 20 characters and does not have special character restrictions. The maximum length of ACTARMCD is longer than for other short variables to accommodate the kind of values that are likely to be needed for crossover trials.

label: Description of Actual Arm
IGcomment: Description of actual Arm. When an Arm is not planned (not in Trial Arms), ACTARM will be "Unplanned Treatment". Randomized subjects who were not treated will be given a value of "Not Treated". Values should be "Screen Failure" for screen failures and "Not Assigned" for subjects not assigned to treatment. Restricted to values in Trial Arms in all other cases.

label: Country
IGcomment: Country of the investigational site in which the subject participated in the trial.

label: Date/Time of Collection
IGcomment: Date/time of demographic data collection.

label: Study Day of Collection
algorithm: Calculation: = DMDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if DMDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,DMDTC - RFSTDTC if DMDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Study day of collection measured as integer days.

label: Device Property Short Name
IGcomment: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in DOTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in DOTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g."1TEST"). DOTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: LIFE, INDICATN, COMPOS

label: Device Property Test Name
IGcomment: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in DOTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Shelf Life, Indication (of disease), Composition (of device)

label: Category for Device In-Use
IGcomment: Defines a category of related records. For example, it can be used to define the type of property being defined, such as DIMENSIONS vs. MATERIAL

label: Subcategory for Device In-Use
IGcomment: A further categorization of a measurement or examination. For example, if DOCAT = DIMENSION, DOSCAT might be LENGTH or WIDTH or THICKNESS

label: Result or Finding in Original Units
IGcomment: Result of the Device Property as originally observed or collected. DOORRES should contain the result or value of the property defined in DOTEST. For example, if DOTEST is LIFE (shelf life) then DOORRES might be 6 (months).

label: Original Units
IGcomment: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for DOORRES. Examples: MONTHS, cm

label: Evaluator
IGcomment: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Examples: ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR, RADIOLOGIST.

label: Reported Term for the Disposition Event
IGcomment: Verbatim name of the event or protocol milestone. Some terms in DSTERM will match DSDECOD, but others, such as "Subject moved" will map to controlled terminology in DSDECOD, such as "LOST TO FOLLOW-UP."

label: Standardized Disposition Term
IGcomment: Controlled terminology for the name of disposition event or protocol milestone. Examples of protocol milestones: INFORMED CONSENT OBTAINED, RANDOMIZED

label: Category for Disposition Event
IGcomment: Used to define a category of related records. DSCAT is now an "Expected" variable. DSCAT was permissible in SDTMIG 3.1.1 and earlier versions. The change from "permissible" to "expected" is based on the requirement to distinguish protocol milestones and/or other events from disposition events. DSCAT may be null if there are only "disposition events"; however, it is recommended that DSCAT always be populated.

label: Subcategory for Disposition Event
IGcomment: A further categorization of disposition event.

IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier for the device. It must be unique for each tracked unit of the device under study, and can be at whatever level of granularity the device should be identified (e.g., model or serial number, or combination of identifiers).

label: Unique Subject Identifier
comment: Concatenation of STUDYID and DM.SUBJID (This is a variable for internal system use)
IGcomment: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

label: Sequence Number
IGcomment: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of device records within subject records (if applicable) within a domain. May be any valid number. Should be unique within each SPDEVID.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier. Example: pre-printed line identifier on a Concomitant Medications page.

label: Link ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to- one or a one-to-many relationship. For Example: A single tumor may have multiple measurements/assessments performed at each study visit.

label: Link Group ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship. For example: Multiple tumor measurements/assessments will contribute to a single response to therapy determination record.

label: Reported Term for the Tracking Event
IGcomment: Verbatim or preprinted term for the activity that occurs. Example: Shipped, Returned, Installed, Implanted, Explanted

label: Modified Reported Term
IGcomment: Modified term entered to allow mapping of verbatim term to dictionary term. If DTTERM is modified to facilitate coding, then DTMODIFY will contain the modified text.

label: Standardized Tracking Term
IGcomment: Dictionary-derived text description of DTTERM or DTMODIFY. If an external controlled terminology is used, the name and version of the dictionary used to map terms must be provided in a Define.XML ExternalCodeList element.

label: Category for Device Tracking Event
IGcomment: Define a categorization level for a group of related records. Examples: categorize by tracking event type, for example, DOMESTIC vs. INTERNATIONAL

label: Subcategory for Device Tracking Event
IGcomment: Defines a further categorization level for a group of related conditions or events. A further categorization of the event.

label: Party Responsible for the Device
IGcomment: Person or organization accountable for the device at the conclusion of the action specified in DTTERM. Describes the person or organization that is accountable for the device defined in DTTERM. For example: if DTTERM = SHIPPED, DTPARTY would contain the transfer recipient, e.g., SITE. If DTTERM = IMPLANTED then DTPARTY would contain SUBJECT.

label: Responsible Party Identifier
IGcomment: An identifier for the responsible group/role (e.g. site, subject). The value of the responsible party identified in DTPARTY. For example, if DTPARTY is SUBJECT, DTPRTYID would contain the subject number.

label: Visit Number
IGcomment: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

label: Visit Name
IGcomment: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

label: Planned Study Day of Visit
comment: Based on TV.VISITDY
IGcomment: Planned study day of VISIT. Should be an integer.

label: Date/Time of DT Event Collection
IGcomment: Date/Time of the tracking event information was collected. Will generally be the same as the date the tracking event started, but it can differ.

label: Start Date/Time of Device Tracking Event
IGcomment: Start date/time of tracking event. A tracking event (e.g., SHIPPED, RECEIVED) is usually a point in time, which is why only the start date/time is included. If an event occurs over a longer period, the stop date/time may be included from the SDTM model.

label: End Date/Time of Observation
IGcomment: End date/time of the observation represented in IS0 8601 character format.

label: Study Day of Visit/Collection/Exam
algorithm: Calculation: = DTDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if DTDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,DTDTC - RFSTDTC if DTDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Actual study day of visit/collection/exam expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

label: Study Day of Start of Observation
algorithm: Calculation: = DTSTDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if DTSTDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,DTSTDTC - RFSTDTC if DTSTDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Actual study day of start of observation expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

label: Study Day of End of Observation
algorithm: Calculation: = DTENDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if DTENDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,DTENDTC - RFSTDTC if TUENDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Actual study day of end of observation expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

IGcomment: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of device records within subject records within a domain. May be any valid number. It should be unique within every subject/device combination.

IGcomment: Identifier for a group or block of related records. Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject or a group of subject related records. Example: group records specifying all the settings for a specific imaging scan, such as field strength, repetition time and echo time.

label: Reference ID
IGcomment: Internal or external identifier. This could be a scan code or equivalent.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database.

label: Link ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to- one or a one-to-many relationship. For Example: A single tumor may have multiple measurements/assessments performed at each study visit.

label: Link Group ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship. For example: Multiple tumor measurements/assessments will contribute to a single response to therapy determination record.

label: Device In-Use Test Short Name
IGcomment: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in DUTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in DUTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g."1TEST"). DUTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: COILSTR, CNTMEDIA.

label: Device In-Use Test Name
IGcomment: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in DUTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Coil Strength, Contrast Media.

label: Category for Device In-Use
IGcomment: Defines a category of related records. For example, it can be used to define the type of device for which settings are recorded if DI is not used, for example, if the device is not under study. Alternatively, it could record the type of setting, e.g., HARDWARE vs. SOFTWARE

label: Subcategory for Device In-Use
IGcomment: A further categorization of a measurement or examination. For example, if DUCAT = SOFTWARE, DUSCAT might be NOMINAL or POST-ADJUSTMENT.

label: Result or Finding in Original Units
IGcomment: Result of the measurement as originally received or collected. DUORRES should contain the setting or other device condition in effect at the time the device was used.

label: Original Units
IGcomment: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for DUORRES. Examples: Tesla, mm.

label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
IGcomment: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from DUORRES in a standard format or standard units. DUSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in DUSTRESN. For example, if a test has results "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in DUORRES, and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in DUSTRESC as "NEGATIVE".

label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
IGcomment: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format. Is copied in numeric format from DUSTRESC. DUSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

label: Standard Units
IGcomment: Standardized unit used for DUSTRESC and DUSTRESN. The unit for standardized results may or may not be the same as for the original results.

label: Completion Status
algorithm: Set to NOT DONE if 'ND', 'NA', 'NK' ,' ' have been reported on CRF
comment: Set to NOT DONE if 'ND', 'NA', 'NK' ,' ' have been reported on CRF

label: Baseline Flag
algorithm: Baseline flag set to Y when the assessment is collected at the visit marked as baseline in the trial flowchart

label: Evaluator
IGcomment: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Examples: ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR, RADIOLOGIST.

label: Evaluator Identifier
IGcomment: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in --EVAL. Examples: RADIOLOGIST1 or RADIOLOGIST2

label: Repetition Number
IGcomment: The incidence number of a test that is repeated within a given timeframe for the same test. The level of granularity can vary, e.g., within a time point or within a visit. For example, multiple measurements of blood pressure or multiple analyses of a sample.

label: Name of Device Exposure or Output
IGcomment: Name of the device or the exposure outputs that are delivered or administered via the device. This should match the definitions as described in the trial summary domain and/or the protocol. Example: coronary stent, extracorporeal shock wave treatment, hyaluronic acid

label: Category for Device Exposure
IGcomment: Used to define a category of device exposures. For example, for a subject who had radiation delivered through an implanted catheter, DXCAT could be used to group the radiation records vs. the catheter records.

label: Subcategory for Device Exposure
IGcomment: A further categorization of device exposures. If DXCAT captures the radiation vs. catheter records (see DXCAT), then DXSCAT might capture the type of catheter if more than one was used.

label: Method of Device Exposure
IGcomment: Method of device exposure. Example: Implantation, Injection

label: Exposure per Administration
IGcomment: Amount of DXTRT administered/delivered per administration. Dose if captured as a numeric value. Dose should only appear once in DXDOSE, DXDOSTXT or DXDOSTOT

label: Device Exposure Description
IGcomment: Exposure amounts or a range of exposure information collected in text form. Units may be stored in DXDOSU. Example: 200-400, 15-20. Dose should only appear once in DXDOSE, DXDOSTXT or DXDOSTOT

label: Device Exposure Units
IGcomment: Units for DXDOSE, DXDOSTXT, and DXDOSTOT. Examples: pulses, ml

label: Device Exposure Frequency per Interval
IGcomment: Exposure frequency per interval. Usually expressed as the number of repeated administrations of DXDOSE within a specific time period. Examples: CONTINUOUS, PRN, Q2M (Every 2 months)

label: Total Daily Device Exposure
IGcomment: Total daily exposure of DXTRT using the units in DXDOSU. Total exposure over a period other than day could be recorded in a separate Supplemental Qualifier variable.

label: Intended Device Exposure Regimen
IGcomment: Text description of the (intended) schedule or regimen for the Intervention. Examples: TWO WEEKS ON, TWO WEEKS OFF.

label: Route of Administration
IGcomment: Route of administration for DXTRT. Examples: EXTRACORPOREAL, INTRA-ARTICULAR, HEMODIALYSIS

label: Location of Device Exposure
IGcomment: Anatomic location of exposure. Examples: Left knee, OD

label: Laterality of Device Exposure
IGcomment: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing laterality. Examples: Right, Left, Bilateral

label: Reason for Exposure Adjustment
IGcomment: Describes reason why the exposure was adjusted from protocol-specified or expected exposure levels. Example: PAIN

label: Mood
IGcomment: Mode or condition of the record specifying whether the intervention (activity) is intended to happen or has happened. Values align with BRIDG pillars (e.g., scheduled context, performed context) and HL7 activity moods (e.g., intent, event). Examples: SCHEDULED, PERFORMED. IGcomment: Used to define a category of related ECTRT values.

IGcomment: A further categorization of ECCAT values.

label: Occurrence
IGcomment: Used to indicate whether a treatment occurred when information about the occurrence is solicited. ECOCCUR = 'N' when a treatment was not taken, not given, or missed.

IGcomment: Amount of ECTRT when numeric. Not populated when ECDOSTXT is populated.

label: Dose Description
IGcomment: Amount of ECTRT when non-numeric. Dosing amounts or a range of dosing information collected in text form. Example: 200-400. Not populated when ECDOSE is populated.

label: Dose Units
IGcomment: Units for ECDOSE, ECDOSTOT, or ECDOSTXT.

label: Dose Form

label: Dosing Frequency per Interval

label: Lot Number
IGcomment: Lot Number of the ECTRT product.

label: Location of Dose Administration
IGcomment: Specifies location of administration. Example: ARM, LIP.

label: Laterality
IGcomment: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing laterality of the intervention administration. Examples: LEFT, RIGHT.

label: Directionality
IGcomment: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing directionality. Examples: ANTERIOR, LOWER, PROXIMAL, UPPER.

label: Portion or Totality
IGcomment: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing distribution, which means arrangement of, apportioning of. Examples: ENTIRE, SINGLE, SEGMENT.

label: Fasting Status

IGcomment: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

label: ECG Reference ID
IGcomment: Internal or external ECG identifier. Example: UUID.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number from the ECG page.

label: Link ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to- one or a one-to-many relationship. For Example: A single tumor may have multiple measurements/assessments performed at each study visit.

label: Link Group ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship. For example: Multiple tumor measurements/assessments will contribute to a single response to therapy determination record.

label: ECG Test or Examination Short Name
IGcomment: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in EGTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in EGTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST"). EGTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples :PRMEAN, QTMEAN

label: ECG Test or Examination Name
IGcomment: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in EGTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Summary (Mean) PR Duration, Summary (Mean) QT Duration

label: Category for ECG
IGcomment: Used to categorize ECG observations across subjects. Examples: MEASUREMENT, FINDING, INTERVAL

label: Subcategory for ECG
IGcomment: A further categorization of the ECG.

label: ECG Position of Subject
IGcomment: Position of the subject during a measurement or examination. Examples: SUPINE, STANDING, SITTING.

label: ECG Beat Number
IGcomment: A sequence number that identifies the beat within an ECG.

label: Result or Finding in Original Units
IGcomment: Result of the ECG measurement or finding as originally received or collected. Examples of expected values are 62 or 0.151 when the result is an interval or measurement, or "ATRIAL FIBRILLATION" or "QT PROLONGATION" when the result is a finding.

label: Original Units
IGcomment: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for EGORRES. Examples: sec or msec.

label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
algorithm: Set NORMAL if value in EGORRES is NORMAL, otherwise set to ABNORMAL if value is collected
IGcomment: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from EGORRES in a standard format or standard units. EGSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in EGSTRESN. For example, if a test has results of "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in EGORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in EGSTRESC as "NEGATIVE". For other examples, see general assumptions. Additional examples of result data: SINUS BRADYCARDIA, ATRIAL FLUTTER, ATRIAL FIBRILLATION.

label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
IGcomment: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from EGSTRESC. EGSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

label: Standard Units
IGcomment: Standardized unit used for EGSTRESC or EGSTRESN.

label: Completion Status
algorithm: Set to NOT DONE if 'ND', 'NA', 'NK' ,' ' have been reported on CRF
IGcomment: Used to indicate an ECG was not done, or an ECG measurement was not taken. Should be null if a result exists in EGORRES.

label: Reason ECG Not Performed
algorithm: Set to NOT COLLECTED if EGSTAT is set to NOT DONE
IGcomment: Describes why a measurement or test was not performed. Examples: BROKEN EQUIPMENT or SUBJECT REFUSED. Used in conjunction with EGSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

label: ECG External File Path
IGcomment: File name and path for the external ECG Waveform file.

label: Vendor Name
IGcomment: Name or identifier of the laboratory or vendor who provided the test results.

label: Method of ECG Test
IGcomment: Method of the ECG test. Examples: 12 LEAD STANDARD.

label: Lead Location Used for Measurement
IGcomment: The lead used for the measurement, examples, V1, V6, aVR, I, II, III.

label: Baseline Flag
algorithm: Baseline flag set to Y when the assessment is collected at the visit marked as baseline in the trial flowchart
IGcomment: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be "Y" or null.

label: Derived Flag
IGcomment: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records which represent the average of other records, or that do not come from the CRF, or are not as originally collected or received are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If EGDRVFL=Y, then EGORRES could be null, with EGSTRESC, and (if numeric) EGSTRESN having the derived value.

label: Evaluator
IGcomment: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Should be null for records that contain collected or derived data. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, VENDOR.

label: Evaluator Identifier
IGcomment: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in --EVAL. Examples: RADIOLOGIST1 or RADIOLOGIST2

label: Repetition Number
IGcomment: The incidence number of a test that is repeated within a given timeframe for the same test. The level of granularity can vary, e.g., within a time point or within a visit. For example, multiple measurements of blood pressure or multiple analyses of a sample.

label: Element Code
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

label: Description of Element
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: The name of the Element.

label: Visit Number
IGcomment: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

label: Visit Name
IGcomment: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

label: Planned Study Day of Visit
comment: Based on TV.VISITDY
IGcomment: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

label: Epoch
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected. (See Section 3.2.2).

label: Date/Time of ECG
IGcomment: Date of ECG.

label: Study Day of ECG
algorithm: Calculation: = EGDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if EGDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,EGDTC - RFSTDTC if EGDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: 1. Study day of the ECG, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

label: End Date/Time of Observation
IGcomment: End date/time of the observation represented in IS0 8601 character format.

label: Study Day of End of Observation
algorithm: Calculation: = EGENDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if CMENDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,EGENDTC - RFSTDTC if EGENDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Actual study day of end of observation expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

label: Planned Time Point Name
IGcomment: 1. Text Description of time when measurement should be taken. 2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See EGTPTNUM and EGTPTREF. Examples: Start, 5 min post.

label: Planned Time Point Number
IGcomment: Numerical version of EGTPT to aid in sorting.

label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
IGcomment: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a fixed time point reference (EGTPTREF). Not a clock time or a date time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 duration. Examples: "-PT15M" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by EGTPTREF, or "PT8H" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by EGTPTREF.

label: Time Point Reference
IGcomment: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by EGELTM, EGTPTNUM, and EGTPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Date/time of the reference time point, EGTPTREF.

label: Domain Abbreviation
IGcomment: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

comment: Concatenation of STUDYID and DM.SUBJID

IGcomment: Lot Number of the intervention product.

label: Laterality

label: Directionality

label: Fasting Status

Examples: "W250101", "W25F0102".

label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
IGcomment: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from --STRESC. --STRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

label: Standard Units

IGcomment: The incidence number of a test that is repeated within a given timeframe for the same test. The level of granularity can vary, e.g., within a time point or within a visit. For example, multiple measurements of blood pressure or multiple analyses of a sample.

For example, if a test has results "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in LBORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in LBSTRESC as "NEGATIVE". IGcomment: Upper end of reference range for continuous measurements in standardized units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

IGcomment: For normal range values that are character in ordinal scale or if categorical ranges were supplied (e.g., "-1 to +1", "NEGATIVE TO TRACE").

label: Reference Range Indicator

IGcomment: 1. Indicates where the value falls with respect to reference range defined by LBORNRLO and LBORNRHI, LBSTNRLO and LBSTNRHI, or by LBSTNRC. Examples: NORMAL, ABNORMAL, HIGH, LOW. 2. Sponsors should specify in the study metadata (Comments column in the define.xml) whether LBNRIND refers to the original or standard reference ranges and results. 3. IGcomment: Analysis method applied to obtain a summarized result. Analysis method describes the method of secondary processing applied to a complex observation result (e.g. an image or a genetic sequence).

algorithm: Baseline flag set to Y when the assessment is collected at the visit marked as baseline in the trial flowchart
IGcomment: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be "Y" or null.

IGcomment: Indicator used to identify fasting status such as Y, N, U, or null if not relevant.

label: Derived Flag
IGcomment: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records that represent the average of other records, or do not come from the CRF, or are not as originally received or collected are examples of records that might be derived for the submission datasets.
