label: Indication
IGcomment: Denotes the indication for the intervention (e.g., why the therapy was taken or administered).

label: Dose
IGcomment: Amount of --TRT given. Not populated when --DOSTXT is populated.

label: Dose Description
IGcomment: Dosing information collected in text form. Examples: <1 per day, 200-400. Not populated when --DOSE is populated.

label: Dose Units
IGcomment: Units for --DOSE, --DOSTOT, or --DOSTXT (Examples: ng, mg, mg/kg).

label: Dose Form
IGcomment: Dose form for the treatment. Examples: TABLET, CAPSULE.

label: Dosing Frequency per Interval
IGcomment: Usually expressed as the number of doses given per a specific interval. Examples: Q2H, QD, PRN.

label: Total Daily Dose
IGcomment: Total daily dose of --TRT using the units in --DOSU. Used when dosing is collected as Total Daily Dose.

label: Intended Dose Regimen
IGcomment: Text description of the (intended) schedule or regimen for the Intervention. Example: TWO WEEKS ON, TWO WEEKS OFF.

label: Route of Administration
IGcomment: Route of administration for the intervention. Examples: ORAL, INTRAVENOUS.

label: Fasting Status
IGcomment: Indicator used to identify fasting status. Valid values include Y, N, U or null if not relevant.

label: Reason for Dose Adjustment
IGcomment: Describes reason or explanation of why a dose is adjusted. Examples ADVERSE EVENT, INSUFFICIENT RESPONSE, NON-MEDICAL REASON.

label: Element Code
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

label: Description of Element
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: The name of the Element.

label: Visit Number
comment: Multiple unscheduled visits or non-visits can exist having the same visit ID but with different dates. This might result in duplicate records for the same visit number but with different dates
IGcomment: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

label: Visit Name
IGcomment: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

label: Planned Study Day of Visit
comment: Based on TV.VISITDY
IGcomment: Planned study day of VISIT. Should be an integer.

label: Epoch
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected. (See Section 3.2.2).

label: Date/Time of Collection
IGcomment: Collection date and time of an observation represented in IS0 8601 character format.

label: Start Date/Time of Observation
IGcomment: Start date/time of an observation represented in IS0 8601 character format.

label: End Date/Time of Observation
IGcomment: End date/time of the observation represented in IS0 8601 character format.

label: Study Day of Visit/Collection/Exam
algorithm: Calculation: = MLDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if MLDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,MLDTC - RFSTDTC if MLDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Actual study day of visit/collection/exam expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

label: Study Day of Start of Observation
algorithm: Calculation: = MLSTDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if MLSTDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,MLSTDTC - RFSTDTC if MLSTDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Actual study day of start of observation expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

label: Study Day of End of Observation
algorithm: Calculation: = MLENDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if MLENDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,MLENDTC - RFSTDTC if MLENDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Actual study day of end of observation expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

label: Duration
IGcomment: Collected duration of an event, intervention, or finding represented in ISO 8601 character format. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived.

label: Planned Time Point Name
IGcomment: Text description of time when a measurement or observation should be taken as defined in the protocol. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See --TPTNUM and -- TPTREF.

label: Planned Time Point Number
IGcomment: Numeric version of planned time point used in sorting.

label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
IGcomment: Planned Elapsed time in ISO 8601 character format relative to a planned fixed reference (--TPTREF) such as "Previous Dose" or "Previous Meal". This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration.

label: Time Point Reference
IGcomment: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by --ELTM, --TPTNUM, and --TPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by --TPTREF in ISO 8601 character format.

label: Start Relative to Reference Period
IGcomment: Identifies the start of the observation as being before, during, or after the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics. Note: This variable will be deprecated (phased out) in a future (post SDTM v1.4) release. The functionality of this variable can be replaced by the use of - -STRTPT with --STTPT = RFSTDTC.

label: End Relative to Reference Period
IGcomment: Identifies the end of the observation as being before, during or after the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics. Note: This variable will be deprecated (phased out) in a future (post SDTM v1.4) release. The functionality of this variable can be replaced by the use of - -ENRTPT with --ENTPT = RFENDTC.

label: Start Relative to Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Identifies the start of the observation as being before or after the sponsor- defined reference time point defined by variable --STTPT.

label: Start Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 or other character format of the sponsor- defined reference point referred to by --STRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-15" or "VISIT 1".

label: End Relative to Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Identifies the end of the observation as being before or after the sponsor- defined reference time point defined by variable --ENTPT.

label: End Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 or other character format of the sponsor- defined reference point referred to by --ENRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-25" or "VISIT 2".

label: Study Identifier
IGcomment: Unique identifier for a study.

label: Domain Abbreviation
IGcomment: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

label: Unique Subject Identifier
comment: Concatenation of STUDYID and DM.SUBJID
IGcomment: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

label: Sponsor Device Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier for a device

label: Sequence Number
algorithm: Sequential number identifying records within each USUBJID
IGcomment: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

label: Group ID
IGcomment: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

label: Reference ID
IGcomment: Internal or external procedure identifier.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number from the procedure or test page.

label: Link ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link results of a procedure to the procedure performed.

label: Link Group ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship. For example: Multiple tumor measurements/assessments will contribute to a single response to therapy determination record.

label: Test or Examination Short Name
IGcomment: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in MOTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in MOTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST"). MOTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: VOLUME, INTP

label: Test or Examination Name
IGcomment: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in MOTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Volume, Interpretation

label: Category for Test
IGcomment: Used to categorize observations across subjects.

label: Subcategory for Test
IGcomment: A further categorization.

label: Position of Subject
IGcomment: Position of the subject during a measurement or examination. Examples: SUPINE, STANDING, SITTING.

label: Result or Finding in Original Units
IGcomment: Result of the procedure measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

label: Original Units
IGcomment: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for MOORRES.

label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
IGcomment: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from MOORRES in a standard format or standard units. MOSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in MOSTRESN.

label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
IGcomment: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from MOSTRESC. MOSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

label: Standard Units
IGcomment: Standardized unit used for MOSTRESC or MOSTRESN.

label: Completion Status
algorithm: Set to NOT DONE if 'ND', 'NA', 'NK' ,' ' have been reported on CRF
IGcomment: Used to indicate a test was not done, or a measurement was not taken. Should be null if a result exists in MOORRES.

label: Reason Test Not Performed
IGcomment: Describes why a measurement or test was not performed. Examples: BROKEN EQUIPMENT or SUBJECT REFUSED. Used in conjunction with MOSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

label: External File Path
IGcomment: File path to the external file.

label: Vendor Name
IGcomment: Name or identifier of the laboratory or vendor who provided the test results.

label: Location Used for Measurement
IGcomment: Location relevant to the collection of the measurement. Examples: BRAIN, KIDNEY, LIVER. etc.

label: Specimen Laterality within Subject
IGcomment: Qualifier for laterality of the specimen within the subject for paired specimens. Examples: LEFT, RIGHT, BILATERAL.

label: Specimen Directionality within Subject
IGcomment: Qualifier for directionality of the specimen within the subject. Examples: DORSAL, PROXIMAL.

label: Portion or Totality
IGcomment: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing the portion of totality which means arrangement of, or apportioning of. Examples: ENTIRE, PARTIAL

label: Method of Procedure Test
IGcomment: Method of the test or examination result.

label: Analysis Method
IGcomment: Analysis method applied to obtain a summarized result. Examples: STEREOLOGY

label: Baseline Flag
algorithm: Baseline flag set to Y when the assessment is collected at the visit marked as baseline in the trial flowchart
IGcomment: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be "Y" or null.

label: Derived Flag
IGcomment: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records that represent the average of other records, or that do not come from the CRF, or are not as originally collected or received are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If MODRVFL=Y, then MOORRES could be null, and (if numeric) MOSTRESN having the derived value.

label: Evaluator
IGcomment: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Should be null for records that contain collected or derived data. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, VENDOR.

label: Evaluator Identifier
IGcomment: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in --EVAL. Examples: RADIOLOGIST1 or RADIOLOGIST2

label: Repetition Number
IGcomment: The incidence number of a test that is repeated within a given timeframe for the same test. The level of granularity can vary, e.g., within a time point or within a visit. For example, multiple measurements of blood pressure or multiple analyses of a sample.

label: Element Code
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

label: Description of Element
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: The name of the Element.

IGcomment: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

label: Visit Name
IGcomment: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

label: Planned Study Day of Visit
comment: Based on TV.VISITDY
IGcomment: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

label: Epoch
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected. (See Section 3.2.2).

label: Date/Time of Test
IGcomment: Date of test.

label: Study Day of Test
algorithm: Calculation: = MODTC - RFSTDTC+1 if MODTC is on or after RFSTDTC,MODTC - RFSTDTC if MODTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: 1. Study day of the procedure or test, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

label: Planned Time Point Name
IGcomment: 1. Text Description of time when measurement should be taken. 2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See MOTPTNUM and MOTPTREF. Examples: Start, 5 min post.

label: Planned Time Point Number
IGcomment: Numerical version of MOTPT to aid in sorting.

label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
IGcomment: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a fixed time point reference (MOTPTREF). Not a clock time or a date time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 duration. Examples: "-PT15M" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by MOTPTREF, or "PT8H" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by MOTPTREF.

label: Time Point Reference
IGcomment: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by MOELTM, MOTPTNUM, and MOTPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Date/time of the reference time point, MOTPTREF.

label: Study Identifier
IGcomment: Unique identifier for a study.

label: Sponsor Device Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier for a device

label: Domain Abbreviation
IGcomment: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

label: Unique Subject Identifier
comment: Concatenation of STUDYID and DM.SUBJID
IGcomment: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

label: Sequence Number
algorithm: Sequential number identifying records within each USUBJID
IGcomment: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

label: Group ID
IGcomment: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain to support relationships within the domain and between domains. In MS, used to link to organism in MB.

label: Reference ID
IGcomment: Internal or external specimen identifier. Example: Specimen ID.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database.

label: Link ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to- one or a one-to-many relationship. For Example: A single tumor may have multiple measurements/assessments performed at each study visit.

label: Link Group ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship. For example: Multiple tumor measurements/assessments will contribute to a single response to therapy determination record.

label: Microbiology Organism Finding Short Name
IGcomment: Short name of the measurement, test, or finding described in MSTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in MSTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g."1TEST"). MSTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples for GROWTH findings: EXTGROW, COLCOUNT. For SUSCEPTIBILITY findings, the test is the drug the organism was tested with, i.e. PENICLLN, AMOXCLLN.

label: Organism Test or Finding Name
IGcomment: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. Examples for GROWTH findings: Extent of Growth, Colony Count. Examples for SUSCEPTIBILITY findings: Amoxicillin Susceptibility, Penicillin Susceptibility

label: Category for Organism Findings
IGcomment: Used to define a category of related records. Examples: GROWTH, SUSCEPTIBILITY.

label: Subcategory for Organism Findings
IGcomment: A further categorization of a test category. Examples: CULTURE, ISOLATE

label: Result or Finding in Original Units
IGcomment: Result of the Microbiology Organism measurement or finding as originally received or collected. Examples for GROWTH findings: GROWTH INTO 3RD QUADRANT. Examples for SUSCEPTIBLITY findings:.0080,.0023

label: Original Units
IGcomment: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for MSORRES. Example: mcg/mL

label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
IGcomment: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from MSORRES in a standard format or standard units. MSSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in MSSTRESN. For example, if a test has results "+3 MODERATE", "MOD", and "MODERATE", and in MSORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in MSSTRESC as "MODERATE".

label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
IGcomment: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from MSSTRESC. MSSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

label: Standard Units
IGcomment: Standardized unit used for MSSTRESC and MSSTRESN.

label: Result Category
IGcomment: Used to categorize the result of a finding in a standard format. Example for SUSCEPTIBILITY finding: SUSCEPTIBLE, INTERMEDIATE, RESISTANT, or UNKNOWN.

label: Completion Status
algorithm: Set to NOT DONE if 'ND', 'NA', 'NK' ,' ' have been reported on CRF
IGcomment: Used to indicate a test on an organism was not done, or a test was not performed. Should be null if a result exists in MSORRES or have a value of NOT DONE.

label: Reason Test Not Done
IGcomment: Reason not done. Describes why a measurement or test was not performed. Used in conjunction with MSSTAT when value is NOT DONE. Example: SAMPLE LOST

label: Vendor Name
IGcomment: Name or identifier of the laboratory or vendor that provided the test results.

label: LOINC Code
IGcomment: 1. Dictionary-derived LOINC Code for MSTEST. 2. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the define.xml external codelist attributes

label: Method of Test or Examination
IGcomment: Method of the test or examination. Example: GRAM STAIN, MACRO BROTH DILUTION, AGAR DILUTION

label: Baseline Flag
algorithm: Baseline flag set to Y when the assessment is collected at the visit marked as baseline in the trial flowchart
IGcomment: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be "Y" or null.

label: Derived Flag
IGcomment: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records that represent the average of other records or some other derivation, and those that do not come from the CRF, are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If MSDRVFL=Y, then MSORRES may be null, with MSSTRESC and (if numeric) MSSTRESN having the derived value.

label: Evaluator
IGcomment: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Examples: ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR, RADIOLOGIST.

label: Evaluator Identifier
IGcomment: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in --EVAL. Examples: RADIOLOGIST1 or RADIOLOGIST2

label: Repetition Number
IGcomment: The incidence number of a test that is repeated within a given timeframe for the same test. The level of granularity can vary, e.g., within a time point or within a visit. For example, multiple measurements of blood pressure or multiple analyses of a sample.

label: Element Code
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

label: Planned Study Day of Visit
comment: Based on TV.VISITDY

label: Epoch

IGcomment: 1. Study day of the test, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics. This formula should be consistent across the submission.

Examples: "-PT15M" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by MSTPTREF, or "P8H" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by MSTPTREF.

label: Time Point Reference

label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by --TPTREF in ISO 8601 character format.

IGcomment: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier for a device

label: Focus of Study-Specific Interest
IGcomment: Identification of a focus of study-specific interest on or within a subject or specimen as called out in the protocol for which a measurement, test, or examination was performed.

label: Sequence Number
algorithm: Sequential number identifying records within each USUBJID
IGcomment: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

label: Group ID
IGcomment: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

label: Reference ID
IGcomment: Optional internal or external identifier such as lab specimen ID, or UUID for an ECG waveform or a medical image.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps pre-printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a CRF.

label: Link ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to-one or a one-to-many relationship.

label: Link Group
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship.

label: Short Name of Ophthalmic Test or Exam
IGcomment: Short character value for OETEST used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical format to a horizontal format. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in OETESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). OETESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Example: "NUMLCOR".

label: Name of Ophthalmic Test or Exam
IGcomment: Long name for the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in OETEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Example: Number of Letters Correct for OETESTCD = "NUMLCOR".

label: Ophthalmic Test or Exam Detail
IGcomment: Further description of OETESTCD and OETEST.

label: Category for Ophthalmic Test or Exam
IGcomment: Used to define a category of topic-variable values. Examples: "VISUAL ACUITY", "CONTRAST SENSITIVIY", "OCULAR COMFORT".

label: Subcategory for Ophthalmic Test or Exam
IGcomment: Used to define a further categorization of OECAT values. Examples: "HIGH CONTRAST" and "LOW CONTRAST" when OECAT is "VISUAL ACUITY".

label: Result or Finding in Original Units
IGcomment: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected. Examples: "120", "<1, NORMAL", "RED SPOT VISIBLE".

label: Original Units
IGcomment: Original unit for OEORRES. Examples: "mm", "um".

label: Normal Range Lower Limit-Original Units
IGcomment: Lower end of normal range or reference range for results stored in OEORRES.

label: Normal Range Upper Limit-Original Units
IGcomment: Upper end of normal range or reference range for results stored in OEORRES.

label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
algorithm: OEORRES converted into standard unit
IGcomment: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from OEORRES in a standard format or in standard units. OESTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in OESTRESN.

label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
IGcomment: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from OESTRESC. OESTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

label: Standard Units
IGcomment: Standardized units used for OESTRESC and OESTRESN. Examples: "mm", "um".

label: Normal Range Lower Limit-Standard Units
algorithm: OEORNRLO converted to standard unit (OESTRESU)
IGcomment: Lower end of normal range or reference range for standardized results (e.g., OESTRESC, OESTRESN) represented in standardized units (OESTRESU).

label: Normal Range Upper Limit-Standard Units
algorithm: OEORNRHI converted to standard unit (OESTRESU)
IGcomment: Upper end of normal range or reference range for standardized results (e.g., OESTRESC, OESTRESN) represented in standardized units (OESTRESU).

label: Normal Range for Character Results
IGcomment: Normal range or reference range for results stored in OESTRESC that are character in ordinal or categorical scale. Example: "Negative to Trace".

label: Normal/Reference Range Indicator
algorithm: If OEORRESN > OEORNRHI then OENRIND=HIGH. If OEORRESN < OEORNRLO then OENRIND=LOW. If OEORRESN between OEORNRLO and OEORNRHI then OENRIND=NORMAL.
IGcomment: Used to indicate the value is outside the normal range or reference range. May be defined by OEORNRLO and OEORNRHI or other objective criteria. Examples: "Y", "N"; "HIGH", "LOW", "NORMAL", "ABNORMAL".

label: Result Category
IGcomment: Used to categorize the result of a finding or medical status per interpretation of test results. Examples: "POSITIVE", "NEGATIVE". The variable OERESCAT is not meant to replace the use of OENRIND for cases where normal ranges are provided.

label: Completion Status
algorithm: Set to NOT DONE if 'ND', 'NA', 'NK' ,' ' have been reported on CRF
IGcomment: Used to indicate exam not done. Should be null if a result exists in OEORRES.

label: Reason Not Examined
algorithm: Set to NOT COLLECTED if OESTAT is set to NOT DONE
IGcomment: Describes why an examination was not performed or why a body system was not examined. Example: SUBJECT REFUSED. Used in conjunction with STAT when value is NOT DONE.

label: External File Path
IGcomment: Filename for an external file, such as one for a retinal OCT image.

label: Laboratory/Vendor Name
IGcomment: Name or identifier of the vendor or laboratory that provided the test results.

label: Location Used for the Measurement
IGcomment: Anatomical location of the subject relevant to the collection of the measurement. Examples: "EYE" for a finding record relative to the complete eye, "RETINA" for a measurement or assessment of only the retina.

label: Laterality
IGcomment: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing laterality. Examples: RIGHT, LEFT, BILATERAL

label: Directionality
IGcomment: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing directionality. Examples: "ANTERIOR", "LOWER", "PROXIMAL".

label: Portion or Totality
IGcomment: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing the distribution, which means arrangement of, apportioning of. Examples: "ENTIRE", "SINGLE", "SEGMENT", "MANY".

label: Method of Test or Examination
IGcomment: Method of the test or examination. Example: "ETDRS EYE CHART" for OETESTCD = "NUMLCOR". The different methods may offer different functionality or granularity, affecting the set of results and associated meaning.

label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
IGcomment: Operationally-derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. The value should be "Y" or null.

label: Baseline Flag
algorithm: Baseline flag set to Y when the assessment is collected at the visit marked as baseline in the trial flowchart
IGcomment: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that OEBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

label: Evaluator
IGcomment: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Should be null for records that contain collected or derived data. Examples: INVESTIGATOR, ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE.

label: Evaluator Identifier
IGcomment: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in OEEVAL. Examples: "RADIOLOGIST1" or "RADIOLOGIST2".

label: Repetition Number
IGcomment: The incidence number of a test that is repeated within a given timeframe for the same test. The level of granularity can vary, e.g., within a time point or within a visit. For example, multiple measurements of blood pressure or multiple analyses of a sample.

label: Element Code
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

label: Description of Element
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: The name of the Element.

label: Visit Number
IGcomment: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

label: Visit Name
IGcomment: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

label: Planned Study Day of Visit
comment: Based on TV.VISITDY
IGcomment: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

label: Epoch
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected. (See Section 3.2.2).

label: Study Day of Examination
algorithm: Calculation: = OEDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if OEDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,PEDTC - RFSTDTC if OEDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: 1. Study day of physical exam, measured as integer days. 2. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

label: Planned Time Point Name
IGcomment: Text description of time when a measurement or observation should be taken as defined in the protocol. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See --TPTNUM and -- TPTREF.

label: Planned Time Point Number
IGcomment: Numeric version of planned time point used in sorting.

label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
IGcomment: Planned Elapsed time in ISO 8601 character format relative to a planned fixed reference (--TPTREF) such as "Previous Dose" or "Previous Meal". This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration.

label: Time Point Reference
IGcomment: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by --ELTM, --TPTNUM, and --TPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by --TPTREF in ISO 8601 character format.

IGcomment: Unique identifier for a study.

label: Domain Abbreviation
IGcomment: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

label: Unique Subject Identifier
comment: Concatenation of STUDYID and DM.SUBJID
IGcomment: Unique subject identifier within the submission.

label: Sponsor Device Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier for a device

label: Sequence Number
algorithm: Sequential number identifying records within each USUBJID
IGcomment: Sequence Number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

label: Group ID
IGcomment: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain to support relationships within the domain and between domains.

label: Reference ID
IGcomment: Internal or external specimen identifier. Example: Specimen ID.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined reference number.

label: Link ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to- one or a one-to-many relationship. For Example: A single tumor may have multiple measurements/assessments performed at each study visit.

label: Link Group ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship. For example: Multiple tumor measurements/assessments will contribute to a single response to therapy determination record.

label: Pharmacokinetic Test Short Name
IGcomment: Short name of the analyte or specimen characteristic. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in PCTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST"). PCTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: ASA, VOL, SPG.

label: Pharmacokinetic Test Name
IGcomment: Name of the analyte or specimen characteristic. Note any test normally performed by a clinical laboratory is considered a lab test. The value in PCTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Acetylsalicylic Acid, Volume, Specific Gravity.

label: Test Category
IGcomment: Used to define a category of related records. Examples: ANALYTE, SPECIMEN PROPERTY.

label: Test Subcategory
IGcomment: A further categorization of a test category.

label: Result or Finding in Original Units
IGcomment: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

label: Original Units
IGcomment: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for PCORRES. Example: mg/L.

label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
algorithm: PCORRES converted into standard unit
IGcomment: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from PCORRES in a standard format or standard units. PCSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in PCSTRESN. For example, if a test has results "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in PCORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in PCSTRESC as "NEGATIVE". For other examples, see general assumptions.

label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
algorithm: PCORRES converted into standard unit
IGcomment: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from PCSTRESC. PCSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

label: Standard Units
IGcomment: Standardized unit used for PCSTRESC and PCSTRESN.

label: Completion Status
algorithm: Set to NOT DONE if 'ND', 'NA', 'NK' ,' ' have been reported on CRF
IGcomment: Used to indicate a result was not obtained. Should be null if a result exists in PCORRES.

label: Reason Test Not Done
algorithm: Set to NOT COLLECTED if PCSTAT is set to NOT DONE
IGcomment: Describes why a result was not obtained such as SPECIMEN LOST. Used in conjunction with PCSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

label: Vendor Name
IGcomment: Name or identifier of the laboratory or vendor who provides the test results.

label: Specimen Material Type
IGcomment: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. Examples: SERUM, PLASMA, URINE.

label: Specimen Condition
IGcomment: Free or standardized text describing the condition of the specimen e.g. HEMOLYZED, ICTERIC, LIPEMIC etc.

label: Method of Test or Examination
IGcomment: Method of the test or examination. Examples include HPLC/MS, ELISA. This should contain sufficient information and granularity to allow differentiation of various methods that might have been used within a study.

label: Analysis Method
IGcomment: Analysis method applied to obtain a summarized result. Analysis method describes the method of secondary processing applied to a complex observation result (e.g. an image or a genetic sequence).

label: Fasting Status
IGcomment: Indicator used to identify fasting status.

label: Baseline Flag
algorithm: Baseline flag set to Y when the assessment is collected at the visit marked as baseline in the trial flowchart
IGcomment: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be "Y" or null.

label: Derived Flag
IGcomment: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be Y or null. Records that represent the average of other records, which do not come from the CRF, are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If PCDRVFL=Y, then PCORRES may be null with PCSTRESC, and (if numeric) PCSTRESN having the derived value.

label: Lower Limit of Quantitation
IGcomment: Indicates the lower limit of quantitation for an assay. Units should be those used in PCSTRESU.

label: Upper Limit of Quantitation
IGcomment: Indicates the upper limit of quantitation for an assay. Units should be those used in PCSTRESU.

label: Short Name of Pharmacogenomics Lab Test
IGcomment: Short character value for PFTEST used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical format to a horizontal format. The short value can be up to 8 characters. Examples: AA, NUC, ALE, PVAL, FOLDCHG.

label: Name of Pharmacogenomics Lab Test
IGcomment: Long name for PFTESTCD. Examples: Amino Acid, Nucleotide, Allele, P Value, Fold Change.

label: Pharmacogenomics Lab Test Detail
IGcomment: Further description of PFTESTCD and PFTEST. This would be used to represent specific attributes, such as the level of granularity for genotyping results or the type of assessment drawn from gene expression results.

label: Genetic Region of Interest
IGcomment: The portion of the genome serving as a locus for the experiment/test. Often the short name, or symbol, for a gene. For human genetic data, these are typically obtained from the gene symbol list maintained by HGNC. Examples: EGFR, KRAS, CYP2D6

label: Type of Genetic Region of Interest
IGcomment: The type of portion of the genome serving as a locus for the experiment/test. Examples: GENE, SECTOR, PROTEIN

label: Reference Sequence
IGcomment: A unique identifier for the reference sequence used to identify the genetic variation. Examples: NM_001234, rs02973492

label: Genetic Location of Interest
IGcomment: Specifies the location within the sequence pertaining to the value in PFGENTRG.

label: Genetic Target
IGcomment: The nucleotide or amino acid being targeted. PFGENLI and PFGENTRG are used only when the test/experiment measures or detects a specific variation to the exclusion of all others.

label: Category for Pharmacogenomics Test
IGcomment: Used to define a category of topic-variable values. Examples: GENE EXPRESSION, GENETIC VARIATION

label: Subcategory for Pharmacogenomics Test
IGcomment: Used to define a further categorization of PFCAT values.

label: Non-Host Species
IGcomment: Biological classification for a microorganism capable of breeding and producing offspring. Examples: HCV, HIV

label: Non-Host Strain
IGcomment: A genetic variant or subtype of a microorganism. Examples: 1a, 1b.

label: Result or Finding in Original Units
IGcomment: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected. For genetic variation, the observed value. Examples: 34.832, NVP, T, Gly, del

label: Original Units
IGcomment: Unit for PFORRES, if applicable. Examples: copies/5uL, Cycles

label: Reference Result in Original Units
IGcomment: Reference result for the measurement or finding, in the same format as PFORRES. PFORREF uses the same units as PFORRES, if applicable.

label: Genetic Location
IGcomment: Specifies the location within a sequence for the observed value in PFORRES.

label: Genetic Sub-Region
IGcomment: The portion of the locus in which the variation was found. Examples: Exon 15, Kinase sector.

label: Result or Finding in Standard Format
IGcomment: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from PFORRES in a standard format or in standard units. PFSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in PFSTRESN.

label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
IGcomment: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from PFSTRESC. PFSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings

label: Standard Units
IGcomment: Standardized units used for PFSTRESC and PFSTRESN.

label: Reference SNP Cluster ID Number
IGcomment: The identifier (rs#) for the observed variation in the dbSNP database.

label: Allele (Chromosome) Identifier
IGcomment: Used to differentiate between copies of a gene on homologous chromosome pairs.

label: Result Category
IGcomment: Used to categorize the result of a finding. Examples: PRESENT, WILDTYPE, RESISTANT VARIANT

label: Completion Status
algorithm: Set to NOT DONE if 'ND', 'NA', 'NK' ,' ' have been reported on CRF
IGcomment: Used to indicate that a test was not done, or was attempted but did not generate a result. Should be null or have a value of NOT DONE.

label: Reason Test Not Done
IGcomment: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with PFSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

label: Raw Data File or Life Science Identifier
IGcomment: Filename for an external file, such as one for a full sequence transcript or a microarray MAGE tab.

label: Vendor Name
IGcomment: Name or identifier of the laboratory or biotech firm that provided the test results.

label: Specimen Type
IGcomment: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. Examples: DNA, RNA

label: Mutation Type
IGcomment: Used to identify whether the variation is inheritable. Examples: GERMLINE, SOMATIC.

label: Method Code for Test
IGcomment: Method of the test. Examples: DIRECT SEQUENCING, MICROARRAY

label: Run ID
IGcomment: A unique identifier for a particular run of a test on a particular batch of samples.

label: Analysis Method
IGcomment: Analysis method applied to obtain a summarized result. Analysis method describes the method of secondary processing applied to a complex observation result (e.g. an image or a genetic sequence).

IGcomment: Name of the pharmacokinetic parameter. The value in PPTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: AUC All, Time of CMAX, Max Conc.

IGcomment: Used to define a category of related records. For PP, this should be the name of the analyte in PCTEST whose profile the parameter is associated with.

label: Parameter Subcategory
IGcomment: Categorization of the model type used to calculate the PK parameters. Examples include COMPARTMENTAL, NON-COMPARTMENTAL.

label: Result or Finding in Original Units
IGcomment: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

label: Original Units
IGcomment: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for PPORRES. Example: ng/L.

label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
IGcomment: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from PPORRES in a standard format or standard units. PPSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in PPSTRESN.

label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
IGcomment: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from PPSTRESC. PPSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

label: Standard Units
IGcomment: Standardized unit used for PPSTRESC and PPSTRESN.

label: Completion Status
algorithm: Set to NOT DONE if 'ND', 'NA', 'NK' ,' ' have been reported on CRF
IGcomment: Used to indicate that a parameter was not calculated. Should be null if a result exists in PPORRES.

label: Reason Parameter Not Calculated
IGcomment: Describes why a parameter was not calculated, such as INSUFFICIENT DATA. Used in conjunction with PPSTAT when value is NOT DONE.

label: Specimen Material Type
IGcomment: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. If multiple specimen types are used for a calculation (e.g., serum and urine for renal clearance), then this field should be left blank. Examples: SERUM, PLASMA, URINE.

label: Evaluator
IGcomment: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Examples: ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE, INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR, RADIOLOGIST.

label: Evaluator Identifier
IGcomment: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in --EVAL. Examples: RADIOLOGIST1 or RADIOLOGIST2

label: Repetition Number
IGcomment: The incidence number of a test that is repeated within a given timeframe for the same test. The level of granularity can vary, e.g., within a time point or within a visit. For example, multiple measurements of blood pressure or multiple analyses of a sample.

label: Element Code
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: ETCD (the companion to ELEMENT) is limited to 8 characters and does not have special character restrictions. These values should be short for ease of use in programming, but it is not expected that ETCD will need to serve as a variable name.

label: Description of Element
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: The name of the Element.

label: Visit Number
IGcomment: 1. Clinical encounter number. 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

label: Visit Name
IGcomment: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

label: Planned Study Day of Visit
IGcomment: Planned study day of VISIT. Should be an integer.

label: Epoch
comment: Set based on the SE domain
IGcomment: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected. (See Section 3.2.2).

label: Date/Time of Parameter Calculations
IGcomment: Nominal date/time of parameter calculations.

label: Study Day of Visit/Collection/Exam
algorithm: Calculation: = PPDTC - RFSTDTC+1 if PPDTC is on or after RFSTDTC,PPDTC - RFSTDTC if PPDTC precedes RFSTDTC
IGcomment: Actual study day of visit/collection/exam expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

label: Planned Time Point Name
IGcomment: 1. Text Description of time when measurement should be taken. 2. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See VSTPTNUM and VSTPTREF. Examples: Start, 5 min post.

label: Planned Time Point Number
IGcomment: Numerical version of VSTPT to aid in sorting.

label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
IGcomment: Planned Elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a planned fixed reference (VSTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 Duration. Examples: "-PT15M" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by VSTPTREF, or "PT8H" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by VSTPTREF.

label: Time Point Reference
IGcomment: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by VSELTM, VSTPTNUM, and VSTPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

label: Date/Time of Reference Point
IGcomment: Date/time of the reference time point from the PC records used to calculate a parameter record. The values in PPRFTDTC should be the same as that in PCRFTDTC for related records.

label: Planned Start of Assessment Interval
IGcomment: The start of a planned evaluation or assessment interval relative to the Time Point Reference.

label: Planned End of Assessment Interval
IGcomment: The end of a planned evaluation or assessment interval relative to the Time Point Reference.

label: Study Identifier
IGcomment: Unique identifier for a study.

label: Domain Abbreviation
IGcomment: Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

label: Unique Subject Identifier
comment: Concatenation of STUDYID and DM.SUBJID
IGcomment: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

label: Sponsor Device Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier for a device

label: Sequence Number
algorithm: Sequential number identifying records within each USUBJID
IGcomment: Sequence number to ensure uniqueness of records within a dataset for a subject. Should be assigned to be in a consistent chronological order.

label: Group ID
IGcomment: Used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain.

label: Reference ID
IGcomment: Optional internal or external identifier such as lab specimen ID, or UUID for an ECG waveform or a medical image.

label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
IGcomment: Sponsor-defined identifier. Example: pre-printed line identifier on a CRF or record identifier defined in the sponsor's operational database.

label: Link ID
IGcomment: Used to facilitate identification of relationships between records.

label: Link Group ID
IGcomment: Used to facilitate identification of relationships between records.

label: Reported Name of Procedure
IGcomment: Name of procedure performed, either pre-printed or collected on a CRF.

label: Standardized Procedure Name
IGcomment: Standardized or dictionary-derived name of PRTRT. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms in the define.xml external codelist attributes. If an intervention term does not have a decode value in the dictionary then PRDECOD will be null.

label: Category
IGcomment: Used to define a category of procedure values.

label: Subcategory
IGcomment: Used to define a further categorization of PRCAT values.

label: Pre-specified
IGcomment: Used when a specific procedure is pre-specified on a CRF. Values should be "Y" or null.

label: Occurrence
IGcomment: Used to record whether a pre-specified procedure occurred when information about the occurrence of a specific procedure is solicited.

label: Completion Status
IGcomment: Used to indicate when a question about the occurrence of a pre- specified intervention was not answered. Should be null or have a value of NOT DONE.

label: Reason Not Done
IGcomment: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with --STAT when value is NOT DONE.

label: Indication
IGcomment: Denotes the indication for the procedure (e.g., why the procedure was performed).

label: Dose
IGcomment: Amount of PRTRT administered. Not populated when PRDOSTXT is populated.

label: Dose Description
IGcomment: Dosing information collected in text form. Examples: <1, 200-400. Not populated when PRDOSE is populated.

label: Dose Units
IGcomment: Units for PRDOSE, PRDOSTOT, or PRDOSTXT.

label: Dose Form
IGcomment: Dose form for PRTRT.

label: Dosing Frequency per Interval
IGcomment: Usually expressed as the number of doses given per a specific interval.

label: Intended Dose Regimen
IGcomment: Text description of the intended schedule or regimen for the procedure.

label: Route of Administration
IGcomment: Route of administration for PRTRT.

label: Location of Procedure
IGcomment: Anatomical location of a procedure.

label: Laterality
IGcomment: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing laterality.

label: Directionality
IGcomment: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing directionality.

label: Portion or Totality
IGcomment: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing the distribution, which means arrangement of, apportioning of.

label: End Date/Time of Procedure
IGcomment: End date/time of the procedure represented in ISO 8601 character format.

IGcomment: Study day of end of procedure expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

label: Planned Time Point Number

label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
IGcomment: Planned elapsed time in ISO 8601 format relative to a planned fixed reference (PRTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration.

label: Time Point Reference
IGcomment: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by PRELTM, PRTPTNUM, and PRTPT.

label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by PRTRTREF in ISO 8601 character format.

label: Start Relative to Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Identifies the start of the observation as being before or after the sponsor-defined reference time point defined by variable PRSTTPT.

label: Start Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the sponsor- defined reference point referred to by PRSTRTPT. Examples: "2003-12- 15" or "VISIT 1".

label: End Relative to Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Identifies the end of the observation as being before or after the sponsor- defined reference time point defined by variable PRENTPT.

label: End Reference Time Point
IGcomment: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the sponsor- defined reference point referred to by PRENRTPT. Examples: "2003- 12-25" or "VISIT 2".

label: Link Group ID
IGcomment: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship. For example: Multiple tumor measurements/assessments will contribute to a single response to therapy determination record.

label: Question Short Name
IGcomment: Topic variable for QS. Short name for the value in QSTEST, which can be used as a column name when converting the dataset from a vertical format to a horizontal format. The value in QSTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g."1TEST"). QSTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. See QS Terminology Spreadsheet for specific text for QSTESTCD. Examples: ADCCMD01, BPR0103

label: Question Name
IGcomment: Verbatim name of the question or group of questions used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in QSTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. See QS Terminology Spreadsheet for specific text for QSTEST. Example: Fist, BPR01 - Emotional Withdrawal

label: Category of Question
IGcomment: Used to define a category of related records that will be meaningful to the Reviewer. See QS Terminology Spreadsheet for specific text for QSCAT. Examples: ADAS-COG, MDS-UPDRS.

label: Subcategory for Question
IGcomment: A further categorization of the questions within the category. Examples: MENTAL HEALTH DOMAIN, DEPRESSION DOMAIN, WORD RECALL.

When sponsors apply codelist to indicate the code values are statistically meaningful standardized scores, which are defined by sponsors or by valid methodologies such as SF36 questionnaires, QSORRES will contain the decode format, and QSSTRESC and QSSTRESN may contain the standardized code values or scores.

algorithm: QSORRES converted into standard unit

QSSTRESC should store all findings in character format; if findings are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in QSSTRESN. If question scores are derived from the original finding, then the standard format is the score. Examples: 0, 1. When sponsors apply codelist to indicate the code values are statistically meaningful standardized scores, which are defined by sponsors or by valid methodologies such as SF36 questionnaires, QSORRES will contain the decode format, and QSSTRESC and QSSTRESN may contain the standardized code values or scores.

algorithm: QSORRES converted into standard unit
